description: From Latin cōnsummātus, past participle of cōnsummāre (“to sum up, finish, complete”), from com- (“together”) + summa (“the sum”) (see sum, summation).

adjectives.description: consummate (comparative more consummate, superlative most consummate)

entries.meaning: Complete in every detail, perfect, absolute.
examples: Synonyms: absolute, complete, perfect, sheer, total, utter; see also Thesaurus:total

entries.meaning: Supremely skilled and experienced; highly accomplished; fully qualified.

verbs.description: consummate (third-person singular simple present consummates, present participle consummating, simple past and past participle consummated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To bring (a task, project, goal etc.) to completion; to accomplish.
examples: Synonyms: complete, finish, round off; see also Thesaurus:end

entries.meaning: (transitive) To make perfect, achieve, give the finishing touch.
(transitive) To make (a marriage) complete by engaging in first sexual intercourse.
examples: After the reception, he escorted her to the honeymoon suite to consummate their marriage.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To become perfected, receive the finishing touch.
examples: Synonyms: come to a head, mature, ripe
